w.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/usalenie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Salenie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 239<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 1:22:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=12>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I ask again the simple question, why use pets in the first place.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>The answer is because they do do damage. Sure, a pet may add, at best, 10% to the kill rate.  Why not want that 10%?  A mob dropping 10% faster means less bashing on tanks that needs to be healed and less frequent med breaks for healers.  10% faster means if you have a set time on the raid, you are getting 10% more chaces at drops.  10% faster means getting to an end encounter sooner when people are fresher, still present.  <br><br>Sure we can remove pets and still have 90% of the strength of the raid.  We can also remove the rangers and probably have 90% of the raid.  We can remove the two beefiest tanks and still have 90% of the raid.  We can remove any one of the nuking classes and still have 90% of the raid.  Pets help, just like other classes and their abilities help.  No one class is the sine qua non of a raid, a raid is successful or not because how they all work together.<br><br>** A 10% increase is significant. **<br><br>So why do pet classes want to use pets?  Because that is our balance.  Would you restrict the tanks to not using 2hs weapons?  I mean they would still have all the other weapons to use.  Woud you restict the wizards to only using fire based spells instead of cold or magic?  Take away a magician's pet and what you get is a maybe 75% of a wizard.<br><br>**You invited/allowed a magician or necro on a raid, let him or her be a magician or necro.**<br><br>&quot;But!&quot; I hear you cry, &quot;we do restrict wizards from casting AE spells and sometimes melee have to use 1 or 2 weapons exclusively for aggro management.&quot;  Of course they do.  Not every situation is the same and some cases any classes abilities can be deterimental.  Just because rogues and monks can instill doubt doesn't mean they always should!  But not every inch of every zone that one raids is bad for pets.  Parts of Hate are horribly pathed, others are very predictable.  Just as a warrior needs to know what weapon to use or a wizard which spells to mem, so a pet class needs to know if a pet is appropriate to the situation or not.<br><br>**Pets are situational, just like any other EQ ability.**<br><br>&quot;But I remember this one time in Fear where...&quot;  Of course you do.  We all do.  So do I, stupid jerk, CR was a major pain.  Yes, pets do break mezzes.  But guess what--so do melee's.  Is there an enchanter out there who has never had to yell at a tank for breaking a mez, but only had them broken by pets?  I doubt it.  But a lot of warriors don't break mezzes, and so do a lot of pet classses.  There are any number of tactics we can use to prevent that.  Hot keying /pet back off and /pet get lost are two biggies.  Another is invisibility and hide.  Pets don't have to break mezzes, it isn't hard coded in EQ, it is the fault of the pet caster.<br><br>**Pets don't break mezzes, pet classes break mezzes.**<br><br>So what do we get adding this all together?<br><br>A 10% increase is significant.<br>You have a magician or necro on a raid, let him or her be a magician or necro.<br>Pets are situational, just like any other EQ ability.<br>Pets don't break mezzes, pet classes break mezzes.<br><br>Sounds to me like the real problem with pets on raids is, as the first poster said, people who can't control them and not the pet themself.  So do what you'd do to a a non-pet problem that is killing raids, remove the individuality causing the problem.<br><br>Otherwise the logic is &quot;I was on a raid once with a troll that kept breaking mezzes, therefore, no trolls on my raids.&quot;  That's the logic generic &quot;no pets on any raids&quot; are basically esoupsing.<br><br>But then prejudices aren't logical, and in the end, that's what an anti-pet-in-all-circumstances view point is.<br><br> <p><a href=" http://www.clanbattleaxe.com"><img src=http://www.zipcon.net/~brus/salenie_sig.jpg></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uneebbo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Neebbo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 2:00:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1>   The problem with pets versus people, is that you can either train the person or avoid them. Even the best pet owner can fall down on pet control in time, or be afk at the wrong time. That said, even as a druid I'm in favor of allowing pets (not my own except as a joke). Pets add damage and damage taking (off tanking) and don't require a cleric to res them if they die. However, they do cause a headache for crowd controllers. It is not always necessary to fight just one mob at a time, though, so chanters need to be willing to consider letting the pet tank.<br><br>  What we need (and I'm going to suggest it via my super duper secret code ring connection), is a Next Mob key based on distance from the character. That would improve the targeting nightmare that is the crowd controller's world. (Although I can already hear &quot;old school&quot; players railing about it if it happens.) That would somewhat decrease the need for AOE stuns. Also, pet taunt seems to be near an all time low, though it does work at least.<br><br>  I'm all for letting people be able to use as many of their abilities as is reasonable. Fortunately, I don't run any raids. ;-P There will still be times when pathing and fears and other such fun make pets untenable.<br><br>  What do raid enchanters think? Would that be enough of a help to let you allow pets to whack on mobs for a little bit while you mezz?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uqnyyen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>qnyyen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 2:20:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> pets</span><hr size=1>   I dont' care how &quot;Great&quot; you are at controlling your pet. I think I can control mine pretty well.. But it doesn't matter how good you can control the pet in certian zones.. You can do everything right and still get the raid whiped out.. One mob casting an AE before it path's will make that pet run.. More than likely, you can go ahead and start your CR at this point..<br>  <br>  I love using my pet, and wish i could in ToV, Hate, wherever.. But i can't.. So nuke nad make Modrods until you get your Pet Disicipline.. <br><br>  Sacrificing maybe 500-1000 damage per mob, (depending on raid zone) is well worth no chance of Pet whipeout.. So... IMO, just suck it up and dont' worry about the pets on raids till you get the discipline..<br><br>  If your having a problem in Non-Raid zones with it, you just need to stand up during pulls.. Its not that hard..<br><br>  So all i can say is, if you wanna raid and use pets, get your disc.. Otherwise, have fun with the CR's.. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Qnyyen <br>Arch Mage<br>Ring of Destiny<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulaidenmaximus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Laiden Maximus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 260<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 2:32:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1> Well, I've been on both sides of this coin.  It's hard to deny that pets do indeed add value in any killing scenario, and it's also a well observed fact that there are times when pets get groups into trouble (caster isn't proficient in pet control, weird aggro, or whatever the case).  In my experiences, its been very situational dependent.  I've grouped with pet-class players that I've felt very comfortable with, and I've also met a few pet-class players that I'm mutually exclusive with (i.e. they leave or I am).<br><br>In a single-group hunting scenario, this is usually more of a nuisance and a time wasting issue (i.e. Enchanter has to cast more mezzes, Cleric ends up healing more, etc, etc etc) than an actual threat to the group.  I have helped many a pet-caster with the various strategies of controlling pets, and unless I'm having a bad day, I'm usually tolerant of a rare mez break.  I guess my thought here is, when the pet-class players (as a whole) begin to experience difficulty finding a group because of their consistent pet problems, they'll find a way to learn a better technique. <br><br>When this becomes a problem in large raiding groups, my approach is to shift to using AOE Mezzes (even for single targets).  The AOE Mezzes have a decently effective Mem Blur effect, and in most cases, after a mez is broken, will not go after the Enchanter (I've run across a few exceptions, but it's a good Enchanter rule of thumb to live by), but instead will go after the mez breaker (or sometimes another nearby person depending on what they've done within sight of the mob while mezzed----e.g. Cleric healing sometimes will pick up a broken-mezzed mob).  In any event, using the technique of standing/sitting near your mezzed mob, it's usually easy to determine who/what is breaking your mezzes.  Assuming the offender is a pet, all I do is track down the owner, call him/her out in /ooc in front of the entire raid, and then let the mob grind the caster into the turf (/gasp).  Darwin usually wins out pretty fast, and repeat offenders will usually quickly tire of being embarrassed in front of the whole group as someone that can't control their pet (pet casters *do* take pride in that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) and of taking an accompanying unnecessary loss of exp.  I never tell a pet-caster that he/she is not permitted to summon their pet.  I let them figure it out for themselves.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>I suppose I've made a few enemies along the way (referring to waiting until a broken-mezzed mob wastes the offender before re-mezzing), but I sincerely believe that I have had more people thank me later for that lesson than curse me.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br><br>Farre<br>Phantasmist <p></p><i></i></td>