aks a mez or you just can't pull the pet off because the mob won't stop hitting it.<br><br>1) hit that hotkeyed button until your finger breaks to try and get the pet off the mob.<br><br>2) can't get the pet off the mob, let the chanter KNOW that and tell him/her that you are letting the pet offtank till it dies or wins.<br><br>3) IF pet loses, you better damn well make sure the mob isn't going after the chanter, take responsiblity for your pet, NUKE the mob, we weren't given Scars of Sigil for nothing. 450dd, 2 sec cast time makes a very nice taunt, maybe now that you have the agro the chanter can mez, if not take yer lumps and go down with dignity.<br><br>Yes tight control of what your pet is attacking is a must, and make damn sure to clear it's agro a couple times during the fight to make sure it stays on the right mob, forgetting to do so will have you pet going after the next mob as soon as the one it was fighting is dead and before the MA is ready to take on the next one.<br><br><br>Pets when quading for 56 damage and backstabbing for 140 damage are a nice asset to a fight.<br><br>&quot;Control, control, you must learn control. ~ Yoda&quot;<br><br>My second favorite line, heard recently about my water pet.<br><br>&quot;Hey, this pet backstabs... cool !&quot;<br><br>But it only takes a few to make a bad rep for all in that class.<br><br>ie.<br>Druids are greedy bastards because they quad everything in sight.<br><br>Rangers are a useless melee class, they have less hps than a will-o-wisp and are major mana sponges because of this.<br><br>Wizards suck in groups, always overnuking and having to be healed like 10 times in a fight.<br><br>These are just a few of the things that go around and cause bad feelings between classes making it hard to get into a group.<br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.shaw.ca/dren/Poppins.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uthelisstormwalker.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thelis Stormwalker</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 4:50:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1> I'm relatively new to the pet class side of the game, having a beastlord at level 33 now. One thing I have learned is if I am using a pet in a group, to stand back and wait for mobs to be engaged and/or mezzed before even thinking about sending my pet to the main target. Yes, when a mob casts a spell (AoE or whatever) and somehow aggroes my pet, I am already aware because all I am looking at is my pet during a pull. Yes, I have /pet back off on a hot key. If my pet isn't under control by the time the chanter calls out that he/she is mezzing Mob_01, or if it is single pull and my pet won't let it run to the camp, I kill the pet. If things go fine, I will send in pet with another hotkey that /assists MA and announces my target that I am sending pet against. Then I go ahead and melee, since BLs are a melee class. <br><br>If we get an add and I'm hit, I back off and call pet back to clear its hate list. If pet doesn't come back immediately, pet gets killed off, end of story.<br><br>If I am in a situation where a pet is allowed but only if it is kept under strict control, I won't even attempt to melee, myself. All my attention is on my pet and what it is doing. If, after a fight my pet disappears or wanders away from the camp, pet gets killed off, end of story. <br><br>Only thing my mana is good for is pet buffs anyways, since all of the other BL spells are basically useless, so making new pets often won't hinder me in the slightest. No need for bone chips or malachite. Hardly any mana to make em, and only a slight bit to buff em. <br><br>I am hoping as I get higher in level with my BL I won't run into too many problems with groups using the methods I've learned so far. I am sure there are more I need to know, and each situation is different, so I imagine there will be a few bumps along the way. I've no problem going without a pet if need be, because I can melee somewhat effectively. Can't take a hit worth a damn though.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ujabener.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jabener</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 7:48:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1> Rangers have more hit points than rogues, bards, monks, and beastlords.  They are only second to knights and warriors.  Mana sponge only comes into play when someone decides 'hey, the ranger is a tank.'<br><br>(PS i realize you being sarcastic and this is off topic, but it's just something i want to let people in on) <p>-Jabener Half-elven<BR>Ranger of Karana<BR><BR><center><img src="http://www.burningmoon.net/images/Jabener.jpg"></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ugrammaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grammaw</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 532<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/19/02 8:07:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsan